# riotbox-config-version: 7
# ~/.config/riotbox/config — Persistent defaults for riotbox.
#
# This file is *sourced* as a bash script by the launcher, so each setting is
# a real shell statement. Most settings below are written in this form:
#
#     : "${VAR:=value}"
#
# Read it as two parts:
#
#   ${VAR:=value}   Assigns `value` to VAR ONLY when VAR is unset or empty.
#                   If you already exported VAR in your shell — or a riotbox
#                   flag set it — the assignment is skipped and your value
#                   wins. This is the standard bash "default if unset" idiom.
#
#   leading ` : `   `:` is bash's null command: it does nothing and ignores
#                   its arguments. It is here only to carry the expansion so
#                   the line is a harmless no-op. Without it, bash would try
#                   to RUN the expanded value as a command (and fail).
#
# So these are DEFAULTS you can always override at launch — not hard
# overrides. Precedence, highest to lowest:
#
#     host env / riotbox flags  >  this file  >  /etc/riotbox/config  >  built-in
#
# To activate a setting, uncomment the whole line — keep the leading ": ".
# To revert to the default, comment it out or delete the line.
#
# (A few advanced examples further down use a plain `VAR=value` assignment
# instead. That form FORCES a value, overriding the environment; it is called
# out where it appears.)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ── Network isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Set to "none" to disable outbound network access inside the container.
# This prevents Claude from fetching packages or reaching external services,
# but also blocks exfiltration. Useful for auditing untrusted code.
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_NETWORK:=none}"

# ── Overlay mode (podman only) ───────────────────────────────────────────
# When enabled, project directories are mounted via fuse-overlayfs so that
# changes stay inside the container until you explicitly accept them with
# riotbox overlay-accept. Requires podman and /dev/fuse.
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_OVERLAY:=1}"

# ── Nested containers (podman-in-podman) ─────────────────────────────────
# Passes --device /dev/fuse and --security-opt label=disable to the
# container, allowing Claude to run podman/docker inside the riotbox.
# WARNING: This disables SELinux confinement — the container has reduced
# isolation from the host.
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_NESTED:=1}"

# ── Extra container-engine run-time arguments (relief valve) ─────────────
# Raw flags inserted into the `podman run` (or `docker run`) command after all
# other RiotBox-managed flags, immediately before the `-w` working-directory
# flag and the image name. A relief valve for run-time needs without a
# dedicated setting — e.g. GPU access:
#
#   : "${RIOTBOX_EXTRA_ARGS:=--device nvidia.com/gpu=all --security-opt=label=disable}"
#
# SECURITY: these flags bypass RiotBox's curated safety defaults and can weaken
# container isolation. Whitespace-separated and word-split like every other
# flag block — a single value may NOT contain spaces (e.g. a bind-mount path
# with a space is unsupported here). A bare `--` is rejected unconditionally
# (even with _ACK=1), since it would end the engine's option parsing. When set,
# the launcher prints a WARNING and a [y/N] confirmation (default No) on every
# interactive launch. To suppress the prompt on every launch, set the
# acknowledgement flag in this file:
#
#   : "${RIOTBOX_EXTRA_ARGS_ACK:=1}"
#
# Without _ACK=1 and without a TTY (CI/scripts), the launch ABORTS rather than
# silently applying the flags.
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_EXTRA_ARGS:=}"
# : "${RIOTBOX_EXTRA_ARGS_ACK:=1}"

# ── Container image name ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Override if you maintain multiple RiotBox images (e.g. per-project).
#
# : "${IMAGE_NAME:=riotbox}"

# ── Agent selection ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Choose between Claude Code and opencode for `run`/`resume`/`shell`
# commands. Inside the container both binaries are always on PATH; this
# setting only affects which one the convenience verbs invoke. May also
# be overridden per-invocation with the --agent=<name> flag.
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_AGENT:=claude}"

# ── Provider env var & routing passthrough ──────────────────────────────
# Controls which env vars are forwarded from your host shell into the
# container, and lets you inject new ones computed at launch time.
#
# Two entry forms (entries are parsed line-by-line):
#
#   bare NAME      Forward NAME from host env. Skipped silently if NAME
#                  is unset or empty on the host. Multiple bare names
#                  may appear on one line, whitespace-separated (BC).
#
#   KEY=VALUE      Set KEY inside the container. VALUE is bash-expanded
#                  at the time this file is sourced — so $BAR pulls from
#                  the host shell, $(cmd) runs a command, and literals
#                  are passed through verbatim. KEY=VALUE entries must
#                  be on their own line; values may contain spaces.
#
# Comment lines starting with `#` and blank lines are skipped.
#
# DEFAULT (when this variable is unset): the union of every registered
# agent's `agent_<name>_env_vars` declaration, deduplicated. Each agent
# manifest at agents/<name>/manifest.sh is the source of truth for the
# vars THAT agent reads — adding a provider key means editing one
# manifest, not this config and not passthrough-vars.sh.
#
# Today that default covers:
#   * Claude Code (agents/claude/manifest.sh): ANTHROPIC_API_KEY,
#     ANTHROPIC_AUTH_TOKEN, ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL, ANTHROPIC_VERTEX_*,
#     ANTHROPIC_BEDROCK_BASE_URL, CLAUDE_CODE_USE_VERTEX,
#     CLAUDE_CODE_USE_BEDROCK, VERTEX_LOCATION, CLOUD_ML_REGION,
#     AWS_REGION, AWS_PROFILE.
#   * opencode (agents/opencode/manifest.sh): ANTHROPIC_API_KEY,
#     OPENAI_API_KEY, OPENROUTER_API_KEY, GEMINI_API_KEY, GROQ_API_KEY,
#     MISTRAL_API_KEY, DEEPSEEK_API_KEY, XAI_API_KEY.
#
# Setting RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS REPLACES the default — it does not
# merge. If you set it, list everything you want forwarded. To ADD to
# whichever set is active (default OR your override) without replacing
# it, use RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_EXTRA_VARS (documented below).
#
# Security:
#   * Sensitive values from KEY=VALUE entries never appear in `ps`/argv —
#     the launcher exports them into its own env and passes only `-e KEY`
#     (no `=value`) to podman.
#   * Use double quotes (or no quotes) around the string so bash expands
#     $VAR / $(cmd) at source time; single quotes suppress expansion.
#   * `set -u` is active when this file is sourced — `FOO=$BAR` with BAR
#     unset will ABORT the launcher with `bash: BAR: unbound variable`.
#     For an optional default, use `FOO=${BAR:-}` or `FOO=${BAR:-fallback}`.
#   * Command substitution failures inside an assignment (`FOO=$(missing)`)
#     are NOT caught by `set -e`; the resulting VALUE is empty.
#   * Values must not contain newlines. For multiline values, define and
#     export the variable in this file as a separate statement and pass
#     it by bare name.
#
# Excluded from the default by design — uncomment in your shell to opt in:
#   * AWS access keys (AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID, AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY,
#     AWS_SESSION_TOKEN) — long-lived static keys in an autonomous
#     container is a security regression. Prefer AWS_PROFILE +
#     AWS_SHARED_CREDENTIALS_FILE (handled by RIOTBOX_CREDFILE_VARS).
#   * SSH_AUTH_SOCK — Unix socket forwarding has a different mount
#     model and gives the container live signing access for the host
#     SSH agent's lifetime; out of scope here.
#
# Examples:
#
# Single-line, bare names only (BC with prior versions). The `: "${VAR:=...}"`
# default form lets a host-env RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS still win:
# : "${RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS:=ANTHROPIC_API_KEY OPENAI_API_KEY}"
#
# Multi-line, mixed forms. NOTE the plain `VAR="..."` assignment (no leading
# `:`): a multi-line body can't use the `:=` default idiom, so this FORCES the
# value and overrides anything set in the host environment.
# RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS="
#     ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
#     OPENAI_API_KEY
#     PROJECT_NAME=$(basename "${PWD}")
#     GIT_BRANCH=$(git -C "${PWD}" rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD 2>/dev/null || echo unknown)
#     TOKEN=$(cat ~/.secrets/work-api-token)
#     EDITOR=vim
# "

# ── Provider env var passthrough — append-only ──────────────────────────
# Same syntax as RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS (bare names and KEY=VALUE lines,
# multi-line, comments allowed). When non-empty, this is APPENDED to the
# active base — whether the base is the agent-registry default or your
# own RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS override. Use this to add to the set
# without restating it.
#
# Conflict resolution: extras win. A KEY=VALUE in EXTRA_VARS takes
# precedence over a KEY=VALUE OR bare-name entry for the same key in the
# base set. (Mechanism: entries are processed top to bottom; later
# `export` calls overwrite earlier ones.)
#
# Bare-name entries from extras simply add to the set of vars forwarded
# from the host — they don't override anything by themselves.
#
# Validation, security, and shell-expansion rules are identical to
# RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS above. Invalid KEYs abort the launcher.
#
# Examples:
#
# Keep the registry default, just add EDITOR and a token:
# RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_EXTRA_VARS="
#     EDITOR
#     WORK_TOKEN=$(cat ~/.secrets/work-api-token)
# "
#
# Override the default but layer per-invocation extras on top:
# : "${RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_VARS:=ANTHROPIC_API_KEY OPENAI_API_KEY}"
# RIOTBOX_PASSTHROUGH_EXTRA_VARS="
#     GIT_BRANCH=$(git -C "${PWD}" rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD 2>/dev/null || echo unknown)
# "

# ── Credential-file mounts ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Whitespace-separated list of "VAR_NAME:/container/path" entries. For
# each entry where the host env var is set AND points to an existing
# regular file, the file is bind-mounted READ-ONLY at the given
# container path, and the env var inside the container is rewritten to
# that path. Missing files or non-regular targets are skipped with a
# notice (no abort). Use this for cloud SDK credentials that live on
# disk and are referenced by env var.
#
# Defaults cover:
#   * GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS — Vertex / Google ADC
#   * AWS_SHARED_CREDENTIALS_FILE / AWS_CONFIG_FILE — Bedrock / boto3
#   * KUBECONFIG — kubectl
#
# : "${RIOTBOX_CREDFILE_VARS:=GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS:/run/secrets/gcp-creds.json AWS_SHARED_CREDENTIALS_FILE:/run/secrets/aws-credentials AWS_CONFIG_FILE:/run/secrets/aws-config KUBECONFIG:/run/secrets/kubeconfig}"

# ── Internal / test seam (not for everyday use) ──────────────────────
#
# RIOTBOX_FORCE_UNOWNED_MOUNTS forces the unowned-mount branch in
# setup_projects regardless of real path ownership. Two forms:
#
#   =1                 sledgehammer — every project path treated as
#                      unowned (uses :O instead of :z / :ro,z)
#   =/a:/b:…           literal colon-separated list — only paths
#                      whose canonical form matches an entry are
#                      treated as unowned; other paths fall back to
#                      the real ownership check
#
# This exists so venom tests can exercise the unowned-mount code path
# without root-owned fixtures (which can't be created without sudo).
# Production code does not need this set; the real production gate is
# `[ ! -O "$dir" ]` and runs automatically.
#
# RIOTBOX_FORCE_UNOWNED_MOUNTS=

# ── Vertex ADC prompt ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# When CLAUDE_CODE_USE_VERTEX is set on the host but
# GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS is not, and
# ~/.config/gcloud/application_default_credentials.json exists, the launcher
# prompts (TTY only) before bind-mounting that file read-only into the
# container. Decline to manage the credential yourself instead — set
# GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS on the host to point at any credential
# file, or copy a credential file into a project mount. There is no
# config flag to suppress the prompt; the prompt only fires when its
# pre-conditions (Vertex on, GAC unset, ADC file present) are all met.
